   <titles>
      <title>Linear Motion – Explanation</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Just how does an expression like</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{l}(t) = \mathbf{a} + t\cdot \mathbf{v}</latex>
                  </math>,  <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>describe a straight motion with constant speed? – The key is to think of the variable <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math> as time and of the vector <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{l}(t)</latex>
                  </math> as the position vector of the particle at time <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math>. The result is illustrated below.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/LinearMotion_Illstrtn.gif"/>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>In general, the location <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{l}(t)</latex>
                  </math> of the particle at time <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math> is found by starting from the tip of <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{a}</latex>
                  </math> and moving <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math> units in the direction of <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{v}</latex>
                  </math>. As a consequence, for any time <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math>, the displacement of the particle during the time interval <math>
                     <latex>[t,t+1]</latex>
                  </math> is given by</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\mathbf{l}(t+1)-\mathbf{l}(t)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=	</latex>
                     </math>
                     <companion>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Computation of displacement vector</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{l}(t+1)</latex>
                                 </math> is the position vector of the particle at time <math>
                                    <latex>t+1</latex>
                                 </math>; <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{l}(t)</latex>
                                 </math> is the position vector of the particle at time <math>
                                    <latex>t</latex>
                                 </math>. Therefore the displacement of the particle during the time interval <math>
                                    <latex>[t,t+1]</latex>
                                 </math> is given by <math>
                                    <latex>\Vect{l}(t+1)-\Vect{l}(t)</latex>
                                 </math>.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </companion>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\mathbf{a}+(t+1)\cdot \mathbf{v}\ -\ (\mathbf{a}+t\cdot \mathbf{v}) = \Vect{v}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>So <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math> gives the displacement of the moving particle within any time interval of length <math>
                     <latex>1</latex>
                  </math>. This is the reason why we call it the velocity vector.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
